WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.324 align:middle line:84%
[SQUEAKING]
[RUSTLING] [CLICKING]

00:00:05.324 --> 00:00:12.900 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:16.140 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK well, today
is our last day together.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:18.140 align:middle line:84%
I was remembering the
first day at the beginning

00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:20.440 align:middle line:84%
I said to everybody I'm
excited about projection

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:22.840 align:middle line:84%
theory and these basic
problems we just solved

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:24.140 align:middle line:90%
in the last couple years.

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:28.000 align:middle line:84%
And we're trying to
describe the ideas in this.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And the beginning of the class
I say all these things I'm

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:31.980 align:middle line:90%
excited to do.

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:35.220 align:middle line:84%
And I wonder, am I going-- are
we going to manage to do this?

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:37.840 align:middle line:90%


00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:38.580 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, anyway.

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:40.760 align:middle line:84%
Now it's at the end and
we've been working steadily

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:42.460 align:middle line:90%
and done some of it.

00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:45.630 align:middle line:90%


00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:46.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:49.640 align:middle line:90%


00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:54.280 align:middle line:84%
So today we'll try to say the--
finish the story of proving

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:58.200 align:middle line:84%
the sharp projection theorems
and to say the last couple

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:00.690 align:middle line:90%
of ideas that go into it.

00:01:00.690 --> 00:01:03.470 align:middle line:90%


00:01:03.470 --> 00:01:07.410 align:middle line:84%
So the first idea goes back
to the beginning of the class.

00:01:07.410 --> 00:01:11.190 align:middle line:84%
It goes back to using
the Fourier method

00:01:11.190 --> 00:01:14.230 align:middle line:84%
and getting a little
bit more out of it

00:01:14.230 --> 00:01:16.900 align:middle line:84%
than we had realized
at that time.

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:19.750 align:middle line:90%


00:01:19.750 --> 00:01:22.810 align:middle line:84%
And then after that-- so this
thing, I'll do by itself.

00:01:22.810 --> 00:01:25.430 align:middle line:84%
It's like remembering
the Fourier method

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:28.255 align:middle line:84%
and seeing how much
we can learn from it.

00:01:28.255 --> 00:01:30.630 align:middle line:84%
Then I'll remember what was
the whole big theorem that we

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:33.790 align:middle line:84%
wanted to prove, and what are
all the things we knew about it.

00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:40.390 align:middle line:84%
And the last idea in the
class is combining information

00:01:40.390 --> 00:01:42.270 align:middle line:84%
from many different
scales, which

00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:45.190 align:middle line:84%
allows us to combine all
of the previous ideas

00:01:45.190 --> 00:01:48.190 align:middle line:90%
into one big argument.

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:48.880 align:middle line:90%
Master argument.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:52.070 align:middle line:90%


00:01:52.070 --> 00:01:55.830 align:middle line:84%
And this way of combining
scales has only been--

00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:59.450 align:middle line:84%
I would say has only been
around for five years or so,

00:01:59.450 --> 00:02:02.730 align:middle line:84%
and is also something--
it's not that complicated.

00:02:02.730 --> 00:02:07.750 align:middle line:84%
And I think also something
that might be of value

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:10.790 align:middle line:84%
to take with you
away from the class.

00:02:10.790 --> 00:02:11.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:20.110 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.110 --> 00:02:20.610 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:27.120 align:middle line:84%
So part 1 is the well-spaced
case and the Fourier method.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:38.130 align:middle line:90%


00:02:38.130 --> 00:02:39.910 align:middle line:84%
So all of these
things that were--

00:02:39.910 --> 00:02:44.990 align:middle line:84%
these sharp projection theorems,
there's some kind of geometric

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:48.750 align:middle line:84%
measure theory analog of the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:51.350 align:middle line:84%
So for reference, let's remember
first the Szemerédi-Trotter

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:51.850 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:55.180 align:middle line:90%


00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:59.060 align:middle line:84%
And here's the version of it
that will be relevant for us.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:03.530 align:middle line:84%
So if E contained in R2
is a set of N points.

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:07.140 align:middle line:90%


00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:14.100 align:middle line:84%
And L sub r of E is the
set of lines, little l.

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:19.820 align:middle line:84%
So that little l
intersect E is at least r.

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:21.540 align:middle line:84%
Then the question is,
how big could this

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:24.020 align:middle line:90%
be in terms of N and r?

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:28.940 align:middle line:84%
And the conclusion is
that the size lr of E

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:32.060 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by n squared.

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:35.800 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me do a big R
to match some other notation.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:38.610 align:middle line:90%


00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:44.700 align:middle line:84%
N squared over R
cubed plus N over R.

00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:48.860 align:middle line:84%
Is N squared over R cubed
comes from the grid example.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:52.060 align:middle line:84%
And this N over R comes
from a very simple example,

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:54.530 align:middle line:84%
where you just draw
a few lines and you

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:56.110 align:middle line:90%
put R points on each of them.

00:03:56.110 --> 00:04:00.370 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:01.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:04.530 align:middle line:84%
And we're trying to
investigate, to what extent

00:04:04.530 --> 00:04:09.370 align:middle line:84%
this continues to hold if
we replace our pure points

00:04:09.370 --> 00:04:14.770 align:middle line:84%
by some little balls and by our
pure lines by some thin tubes?

00:04:14.770 --> 00:04:17.089 align:middle line:84%
And here is one clean
version of that,

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:18.950 align:middle line:84%
that if the points
are quite spread out,

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:21.610 align:middle line:84%
they're what's
called well-spaced,

00:04:21.610 --> 00:04:24.500 align:middle line:90%
then this holds almost as real.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:30.010 align:middle line:90%


00:04:30.010 --> 00:04:33.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is a theorem of Hong
Wong, Noam Solomon, and me

00:04:33.770 --> 00:04:38.330 align:middle line:90%
from around 2018 or something.

00:04:38.330 --> 00:04:44.320 align:middle line:84%
So E contained in R2 is
a set of N delta balls.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:47.210 align:middle line:90%


00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:50.350 align:middle line:90%
E is contained in the unit ball.

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:52.470 align:middle line:90%
AND they're well spaced.

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:54.850 align:middle line:84%
They're as spread
out as possible.

00:04:54.850 --> 00:04:59.730 align:middle line:84%
So they obey the condition that
if you take E and you intersect

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:04.050 align:middle line:84%
it with a ball of radius
N to the minus 1/2,

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:07.210 align:middle line:90%
then that's at most around 1.

00:05:07.210 --> 00:05:13.530 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, if I take a
unit square and I subdivide it

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:19.410 align:middle line:84%
into squares of side
length N to the minus 1/2--

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:22.850 align:middle line:84%
that's been chosen so that there
are N squares in this picture.

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:28.694 align:middle line:84%
And then I put 1 or roughly 1
point in each of these squares

00:05:28.694 --> 00:05:32.170 align:middle line:84%
at one delta ball,
then this is what?

00:05:32.170 --> 00:05:35.390 align:middle line:84%
This is our what
our set looks like.

00:05:35.390 --> 00:05:38.590 align:middle line:90%
So this is a well-spaced set.

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:39.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:41.843 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So if the
size of E intersect B,

00:05:41.843 --> 00:05:44.010 align:middle line:84%
is that supposed to be a
delta ball covering number?

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:44.390 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:45.057 align:middle line:90%
Let's make that.

00:05:45.057 --> 00:05:46.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:46.870 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:50.400 align:middle line:84%
That's a delta ball
covering number.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:54.120 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:57.600 align:middle line:84%
And then there's one more
hypothesis, which is OK,

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:06.640 align:middle line:84%
so then we could say what TR of
E is the set of delta tubes T,

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:12.760 align:middle line:84%
so that T intersect E
delta is at least R.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:15.640 align:middle line:84%
And here, if you take
such a delta tube

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:17.720 align:middle line:84%
and you wiggle it
imperceptibly, you

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:19.180 align:middle line:84%
will have another
such delta tube.

00:06:19.180 --> 00:06:21.240 align:middle line:84%
And we want to count
those as being the same.

00:06:21.240 --> 00:06:23.930 align:middle line:84%
So I'll put here
essentially distinct.

00:06:23.930 --> 00:06:28.440 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:29.346 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:29.346 --> 00:06:32.420 align:middle line:84%
Now there's one
other hypothesis,

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:34.440 align:middle line:84%
which is that R is
not too small, which

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:35.860 align:middle line:90%
I'll explain in a minute.

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:39.600 align:middle line:84%
The hypothesis says R is at
least a little bit bigger

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.920 align:middle line:90%
than delta times E delta.

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:46.880 align:middle line:84%
And then the conclusion
is almost the same

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:57.110 align:middle line:84%
as before, that TR of E is less
same same squared over R cubed.

00:06:57.110 --> 00:06:59.590 align:middle line:84%
This two tildes
here means that it's

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:02.830 align:middle line:84%
hiding something like
a delta to the epsilon

00:07:02.830 --> 00:07:04.630 align:middle line:90%
or something like that.

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:08.710 align:middle line:84%
But it looks almost
the same as this.

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:11.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's compare
these two theorems.

00:07:11.990 --> 00:07:14.670 align:middle line:84%
One difference is that
in the first theorem,

00:07:14.670 --> 00:07:16.750 align:middle line:84%
we had an extra term
here, which I have not

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:19.230 align:middle line:90%
written in the second theorem.

00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:22.790 align:middle line:84%
And the reason is that this
second term is relevant

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:26.390 align:middle line:84%
when R is bigger than
the square root of N.

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:33.990 align:middle line:84%
So the second term, this
dominates if and only

00:07:33.990 --> 00:07:38.070 align:middle line:84%
if R is bigger than
square root of N.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:40.030 align:middle line:84%
But in the well
space case, it's not

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:43.710 align:middle line:84%
possible for a tube to have more
than square root of N points

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:46.540 align:middle line:84%
on it, so this
case never arises.

00:07:46.540 --> 00:07:47.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:49.740 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we
don't have that.

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:53.060 align:middle line:84%
The other difference is that
we added this lower bound on R.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:07:55.820 align:middle line:84%
So let me explain
why we did that.

00:07:55.820 --> 00:07:58.980 align:middle line:90%
So remark.

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:09.060 align:middle line:84%
An average for a
random delta tube T,

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:15.620 align:middle line:84%
the expected size of T
intersect E, that's covering,

00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:20.100 align:middle line:84%
that would be delta
times E delta.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:21.785 align:middle line:84%
This is for each of
these delta points,

00:08:21.785 --> 00:08:23.160 align:middle line:84%
each of these
little delta balls,

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:25.860 align:middle line:84%
there are this many of
them, the probability

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:28.020 align:middle line:84%
that a random delta
tube intersects

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:29.230 align:middle line:90%
that point is about delta.

00:08:29.230 --> 00:08:31.759 align:middle line:90%


00:08:31.759 --> 00:08:32.259 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:32.259 --> 00:08:37.059 align:middle line:84%
SO if you just take any old
tube, you'll have that many.

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:39.659 align:middle line:84%
You'll hit that many
delta balls from E--

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:42.640 align:middle line:84%
tubes that hit this many delta
balls of E are not special.

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:45.420 align:middle line:90%
Any old tube will do.

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:48.723 align:middle line:84%
So if R takes that value, this
upper bound isn't true at all.

00:08:48.723 --> 00:08:50.140 align:middle line:84%
This could be way
bigger than that

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:52.980 align:middle line:84%
because it could be
basically all the tubes.

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:57.980 align:middle line:84%
But rather remarkably-- there's
a rather remarkably sharp phase

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:01.540 align:middle line:84%
transition that you increase R
just a little bit beyond this

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:04.540 align:middle line:84%
threshold, and then you
get a bound that matches

00:09:04.540 --> 00:09:06.062 align:middle line:90%
Szemerédi-Trotter.

00:09:06.062 --> 00:09:10.220 align:middle line:90%


00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:11.152 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:11.152 --> 00:09:15.620 align:middle line:84%
So that is the statement
of the theorem.

00:09:15.620 --> 00:09:18.700 align:middle line:84%
And it says in a nutshell that
Szemerédi-Trotter basically

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:22.100 align:middle line:84%
continues to hold if you
take a well-spaced set,

00:09:22.100 --> 00:09:24.360 align:middle line:84%
which is one of the cases
we mentioned last time.

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:27.460 align:middle line:90%


00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:30.280 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about the statement?

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:37.940 align:middle line:90%


00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:41.070 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to do a proof
sketch of this theorem.

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:48.490 align:middle line:90%


00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:52.850 align:middle line:84%
So let me first mention the
tools that will go into it.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:56.490 align:middle line:90%
There's the Fourier method.

00:09:56.490 --> 00:09:58.210 align:middle line:90%
There's double counting.

00:09:58.210 --> 00:10:01.120 align:middle line:84%
And then there's-- I guess I'll
call this playing with different

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:01.620 align:middle line:90%
scales.

00:10:01.620 --> 00:10:08.970 align:middle line:90%


00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:12.930 align:middle line:84%
The theme of this last class is
playing with different scales,

00:10:12.930 --> 00:10:16.570 align:middle line:84%
which is a simple sounding and
old idea, which nevertheless,

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:23.270 align:middle line:84%
people recently have found a
lot of new ways of doing it.

00:10:23.270 --> 00:10:23.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:26.410 align:middle line:90%


00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:26.910 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:29.760 align:middle line:84%
So let me start with
the Fourier method.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:32.290 align:middle line:90%


00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:35.450 align:middle line:84%
Let me label this
list of hypotheses.

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:36.170 align:middle line:90%
Hypotheses.

00:10:36.170 --> 00:10:43.348 align:middle line:90%


00:10:43.348 --> 00:10:47.720 align:middle line:90%
And Fourier method.

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:48.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:49.860 align:middle line:90%
So it's been a while.

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:51.800 align:middle line:84%
In lectures 3 and
4 of this class,

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:54.920 align:middle line:84%
we developed a Fourier analytic
method to estimate stuff

00:10:54.920 --> 00:10:56.080 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:58.580 align:middle line:84%
And if we had kept
having problem sets,

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:00.240 align:middle line:84%
and if I had been
really clever, I

00:11:00.240 --> 00:11:02.820 align:middle line:84%
would have had you remember
it on the last problem set,

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:05.760 align:middle line:90%
getting ready for this lecture.

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:08.280 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:10.880 align:middle line:84%
If you take the method
exactly the way we did it back

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:14.400 align:middle line:84%
at the beginning
of the class, say

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:22.840 align:middle line:84%
that if we have the hypotheses,
then the size of TR of E

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:25.330 align:middle line:90%
will be bounded by delta--

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:28.600 align:middle line:90%


00:11:28.600 --> 00:11:29.860 align:middle line:90%
OK, I have to actually check.

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:37.360 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:45.120 align:middle line:84%
Delta inverse E delta
R to the minus 2.

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:48.823 align:middle line:84%
I considered redoing
this in the last class

00:11:48.823 --> 00:11:51.240 align:middle line:84%
to remind us all, because I
don't expect it really to have

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:53.760 align:middle line:90%
it on the tip of your brain.

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:56.480 align:middle line:84%
But I decided it was not
that much fun for a thing

00:11:56.480 --> 00:11:58.600 align:middle line:84%
to do in the last
class, and also

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:01.680 align:middle line:84%
that I had to manage the time
to explain the other stuff.

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:04.020 align:middle line:84%
So I'd like to take
this as a black box,

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:06.560 align:middle line:84%
that it's something you
can do with the tools

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:08.180 align:middle line:90%
that we've already have.

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:10.840 align:middle line:90%


00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:11.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:16.612 align:middle line:90%


00:12:16.612 --> 00:12:20.960 align:middle line:84%
Now how does this
compare to our goal?

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:25.920 align:middle line:84%
This E delta, by the way, is
N. So this is delta inverse N R

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:26.940 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2.

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:30.200 align:middle line:90%


00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:32.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, it depends on
how delta and N and R

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:34.400 align:middle line:90%
are related to each other.

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:37.710 align:middle line:84%
But there's a particular
case where it just

00:12:37.710 --> 00:12:41.510 align:middle line:90%
gives exactly the right thing.

00:12:41.510 --> 00:12:52.670 align:middle line:84%
In a particular case is that
if R is the smallest that it's

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:54.190 align:middle line:90%
allowed to be--

00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:59.140 align:middle line:84%
so let's say it is delta to the
minus epsilon delta E delta.

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:04.482 align:middle line:90%


00:13:04.482 --> 00:13:08.950 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, if I solve
for the delta inverse,

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:18.350 align:middle line:84%
delta inverse would be around N
over R. And then I plug in here.

00:13:18.350 --> 00:13:22.270 align:middle line:84%
And I get the one
that this is N over R,

00:13:22.270 --> 00:13:25.270 align:middle line:90%
is N squared over R cubed.

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:26.940 align:middle line:84%
And this is
Szemerédi-Trotter bound.

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:34.700 align:middle line:90%


00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:37.140 align:middle line:84%
So this Fourier method
actually gives the right

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:39.050 align:middle line:90%
answer in an interesting case.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:42.380 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:49.900 align:middle line:84%
But then if you make R bigger,
then if you do this computation,

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:52.220 align:middle line:90%
this ends up being bigger.

00:13:52.220 --> 00:13:55.590 align:middle line:84%
And this will be bigger
than N squared over R cubed.

00:13:55.590 --> 00:14:01.140 align:middle line:90%


00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:03.744 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:03.744 --> 00:14:05.700 align:middle line:84%
Now another
interesting basic thing

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.660 align:middle line:84%
about this that is
perhaps surprising

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:13.020 align:middle line:84%
is that as delta--
if delta gets bigger,

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:17.060 align:middle line:84%
the right-hand
side gets smaller.

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So as we make our tubes thicker,
we actually get a better bound.

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:26.896 align:middle line:90%


00:14:26.896 --> 00:14:33.200 align:middle line:84%
So if R is bigger-- this
is the smallest R could be.

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:35.820 align:middle line:84%
So the other options that
R is bigger than this.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:41.460 align:middle line:84%
So delta to the minus epsilon
delta E delta is less than R.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:44.420 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that R is less
than the square root of N.

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:46.460 align:middle line:84%
Because as we
mentioned earlier, R

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:49.420 align:middle line:84%
can't be any bigger than
the square root of N.

00:14:49.420 --> 00:14:50.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:50.620 --> 00:15:01.460 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm going to set a scale
rho so that rho times N is

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:15.780 align:middle line:84%
around R. Rho times N is
around R. So how big is rho?

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:19.540 align:middle line:84%
Well, rho is going
to be R over N.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:23.180 align:middle line:84%
So it will be smaller
than N to the minus 1/2.

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:25.660 align:middle line:84%
But it will be
bigger than delta.

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:30.610 align:middle line:84%
Because delta N
was smaller than R.

00:15:30.610 --> 00:15:33.190 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
increase delta to rho

00:15:33.190 --> 00:15:37.850 align:middle line:84%
so that rho N will be around
R. So rho will be around there.

00:15:37.850 --> 00:15:43.370 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going
to study E rho, which

00:15:43.370 --> 00:15:52.000 align:middle line:84%
is the rho neighborhood of
E. So let's make a picture.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.530 align:middle line:90%


00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:58.690 align:middle line:84%
Here is the picture of
our well-spaced set E.

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:02.170 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going
to have a scale rho,

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:05.570 align:middle line:84%
which is smaller than this scale
N to the minus 1/2 but bigger

00:16:05.570 --> 00:16:07.010 align:middle line:90%
than delta.

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:14.510 align:middle line:84%
And we'll look at
that guy, E rho.

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:17.770 align:middle line:90%


00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:19.860 align:middle line:84%
And originally, we're
trying to find--

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:23.530 align:middle line:90%


00:16:23.530 --> 00:16:27.170 align:middle line:84%
our original problem is to
understand delta tubes that

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:29.200 align:middle line:90%
hit a lot of balls.

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:33.380 align:middle line:90%
So this might be one.

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:36.720 align:middle line:90%


00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:42.400 align:middle line:84%
This is T delta tube
and TR of E delta.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:46.680 align:middle line:84%
E delta is just E, but I
put the delta to remind us.

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:49.630 align:middle line:84%
But now that we have these
thicker guys, we could study--

00:16:49.630 --> 00:16:53.640 align:middle line:90%


00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:59.960 align:middle line:84%
I could study a rho tube that
contains a lot of rho balls.

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:02.280 align:middle line:90%
So this might be T rho.

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:09.720 align:middle line:84%
That might be a tube that
intersects E rho a lot.

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:12.680 align:middle line:84%
Well, maybe for the same R, but
also maybe for different R's, we

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:13.540 align:middle line:90%
might be interested.

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:16.520 align:middle line:90%


00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:19.060 align:middle line:90%
So now let's make a definition.

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:22.960 align:middle line:90%


00:17:22.960 --> 00:17:29.790 align:middle line:84%
So TR of-- TR tilde
of E rho, this

00:17:29.790 --> 00:17:34.550 align:middle line:90%
is the set of rho tubes T rho.

00:17:34.550 --> 00:17:38.030 align:middle line:84%
So that if I take T rho
intersect it with E rho

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:41.980 align:middle line:84%
and I take its rho covering
number, that's at least R tilde.

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:47.430 align:middle line:90%


00:17:47.430 --> 00:17:50.950 align:middle line:84%
And now the same
argument as before

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:53.350 align:middle line:90%
gives us a bound for this thing.

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:58.140 align:middle line:84%
So if we have our
hypotheses and if R tilde--

00:17:58.140 --> 00:18:01.190 align:middle line:90%


00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:01.890 align:middle line:90%
let's see.

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:05.390 align:middle line:90%


00:18:05.390 --> 00:18:06.970 align:middle line:84%
Well, let me not
keep track of it.

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:17.330 align:middle line:84%
If we have our hypotheses and R
tilde is big enough, then, yeah,

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:19.830 align:middle line:84%
I'll just-- yeah, here we can
put R tilde as at least as big

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:28.220 align:middle line:84%
as R, then TR tilde of E
rho will be bounded by--

00:18:28.220 --> 00:18:32.590 align:middle line:90%


00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Well, we'll have rho
inverse times E delta times

00:18:38.470 --> 00:18:40.150 align:middle line:90%
R to the minus 2--

00:18:40.150 --> 00:18:41.970 align:middle line:90%
times R tilde to the minus 2.

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:48.270 align:middle line:90%


00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:57.550 align:middle line:84%
And this rho
inverse is N over R.

00:18:57.550 --> 00:19:04.734 align:middle line:84%
So that's N squared over
R times R tilde squared.

00:19:04.734 --> 00:19:08.010 align:middle line:84%
Just by thickening the
tubes, we get these bounds.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:10.950 align:middle line:84%
And let me mention an
important special case.

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:19.720 align:middle line:84%
So e.g, TR of E rho is bounded
by N squared over R cubed.

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:34.620 align:middle line:90%


00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:35.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:37.820 align:middle line:90%


00:19:37.820 --> 00:19:45.420 align:middle line:84%
So as it's-- it's a surprising
thing that as we increase rho,

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:48.560 align:middle line:84%
we get a better and better
upper bound for this.

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:53.220 align:middle line:90%


00:19:53.220 --> 00:19:55.860 align:middle line:90%
Now we can't increase it.

00:19:55.860 --> 00:19:57.920 align:middle line:84%
There's a limit to how
much we can increase it.

00:19:57.920 --> 00:19:59.070 align:middle line:90%
Because we do need--

00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:01.700 align:middle line:90%


00:20:01.700 --> 00:20:03.400 align:middle line:90%
we do need this condition.

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:06.500 align:middle line:90%


00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:11.380 align:middle line:84%
So this gives some
upper bound for rho.

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:14.020 align:middle line:84%
But taking rho as close as
you can to that upper bound

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:15.240 align:middle line:90%
is a good idea.

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:18.720 align:middle line:84%
And when we make rho that
big, then we get this.

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:25.450 align:middle line:90%


00:20:25.450 --> 00:20:26.725 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:26.725 --> 00:20:28.900 align:middle line:90%
Now have we proven the theorem?

00:20:28.900 --> 00:20:31.970 align:middle line:90%


00:20:31.970 --> 00:20:33.925 align:middle line:90%
So what I got-- yeah.

00:20:33.925 --> 00:20:34.550 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:20:34.550 --> 00:20:36.310 align:middle line:84%
Just a question about
the bounds there.

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:38.850 align:middle line:84%
You apply the same
Fourier method?

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:40.690 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes.

00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:47.315 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But will the E
delta state not become a rho?

00:20:47.315 --> 00:20:48.190 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:20:48.190 --> 00:20:51.450 align:middle line:90%
So it would be E rho.

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:56.290 align:middle line:84%
But you can maybe
see from the picture.

00:20:56.290 --> 00:21:00.490 align:middle line:90%
Where did we introduce E rho?

00:21:00.490 --> 00:21:07.112 align:middle line:84%
So E rho is equal to E
delta, is equal to N.

00:21:07.112 --> 00:21:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Now that's a
special-- that's where

00:21:08.570 --> 00:21:11.190 align:middle line:84%
we're using that our set
is well-spaced right.

00:21:11.190 --> 00:21:13.890 align:middle line:90%
So that's a great thing to--

00:21:13.890 --> 00:21:15.970 align:middle line:84%
So the so the question
was, should this

00:21:15.970 --> 00:21:18.030 align:middle line:84%
should be a rho
instead of a delta?

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:19.770 align:middle line:90%
And how does that affect things?

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:21.270 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is
yeah, great point.

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:23.490 align:middle line:84%
This should be a rho
instead of a delta.

00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:26.080 align:middle line:84%
But for our set, it
doesn't change anything.

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:30.250 align:middle line:90%


00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:33.410 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at our set, our
set has only one delta ball

00:21:33.410 --> 00:21:36.690 align:middle line:90%
in each N to the minus 1/2 ball.

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:39.090 align:middle line:84%
So when you thicken
them a little bit,

00:21:39.090 --> 00:21:42.470 align:middle line:84%
the number of balls
you see doesn't change.

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:47.790 align:middle line:84%
It's still N. So that is where
we are using this hypothesis.

00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:56.510 align:middle line:90%


00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:58.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, great point.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:00.770 align:middle line:90%


00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:02.626 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:02.626 --> 00:22:08.170 align:middle line:84%
So when I first saw this, I
thought that we were done.

00:22:08.170 --> 00:22:10.090 align:middle line:90%
But it's not quite true.

00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:13.250 align:middle line:84%
So our conclusion
in the theorem is

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:18.080 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to try to
estimate how many of these guys

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:23.680 align:middle line:84%
there are, thin tubes, delta
tubes that have R balls in them.

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:26.680 align:middle line:84%
And we've counted the
number of thick tubes

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:30.200 align:middle line:90%
that have R balls in them.

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:33.420 align:middle line:84%
Now, every thin tube with
R balls, if you thicken it,

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:35.960 align:middle line:84%
you get a thick tube
with at least R balls.

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:40.280 align:middle line:84%
But inside of a thick
tube with R balls,

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:42.460 align:middle line:84%
there may be many thin
tubes with R balls,

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:46.120 align:middle line:84%
and we've only
counted them once.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:49.280 align:middle line:84%
So we do-- we still
have an issue.

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:52.340 align:middle line:84%
That's not super difficult, but
it's important to recognize it.

00:22:52.340 --> 00:22:56.360 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.360 --> 00:23:16.830 align:middle line:84%
So issue 1, rho tube may contain
many tubes of TR of E delta.

00:23:16.830 --> 00:23:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So what would that
scenario look like?

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:25.710 align:middle line:90%
Well, we have our rho tube here.

00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:30.110 align:middle line:84%
And inside we would have
a bunch of delta balls.

00:23:30.110 --> 00:23:35.110 align:middle line:84%
So at least R of them, but
maybe more than R of them.

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:42.590 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that T rho
intersected with E, so

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:47.350 align:middle line:84%
delta, that would be the same
as T rho intersected with E rho.

00:23:47.350 --> 00:23:50.450 align:middle line:90%
Let's say that it's R tilde.

00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:54.830 align:middle line:84%
Which is at R. Might be R
but it might also be bigger.

00:23:54.830 --> 00:24:05.190 align:middle line:84%
And then inside of here we
may have many delta tubes

00:24:05.190 --> 00:24:18.107 align:middle line:90%
that each contain R. OK.

00:24:18.107 --> 00:24:22.270 align:middle line:90%


00:24:22.270 --> 00:24:25.130 align:middle line:84%
So now we have some cousin
of our original problem.

00:24:25.130 --> 00:24:27.770 align:middle line:90%
We have R tilde delta balls.

00:24:27.770 --> 00:24:31.550 align:middle line:84%
And we want to count how
many R-rich tubes there are.

00:24:31.550 --> 00:24:34.630 align:middle line:84%
We don't know as much
about how they are spaced,

00:24:34.630 --> 00:24:39.390 align:middle line:84%
but also we don't need to
have such an incredible bound.

00:24:39.390 --> 00:24:54.190 align:middle line:90%
So by induction, we can assume--

00:24:54.190 --> 00:25:08.150 align:middle line:84%
we can reduce to the case
that each T and TR of E delta

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:13.360 align:middle line:84%
has many delta
balls at both ends.

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:17.768 align:middle line:90%


00:25:17.768 --> 00:25:25.900 align:middle line:84%
So what I mean by
that is here's a tube.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:28.940 align:middle line:84%
So the tube, it has a
bunch of delta balls in it.

00:25:28.940 --> 00:25:32.740 align:middle line:84%
So it means that there
are a bunch at one end

00:25:32.740 --> 00:25:34.200 align:middle line:90%
and a bunch at the other end.

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:37.940 align:middle line:84%
Maybe also a bunch
in the middle.

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:39.670 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's better to
draw what it's not.

00:25:39.670 --> 00:25:46.860 align:middle line:90%


00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:49.130 align:middle line:84%
What it's not is like
they're just all on the left.

00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:53.900 align:middle line:90%


00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:54.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:54.400 --> 00:25:56.180 align:middle line:84%
So in a nutshell,
how would we do this?

00:25:56.180 --> 00:26:00.300 align:middle line:84%
If this was the situation
that all of the delta balls

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:03.300 align:middle line:84%
were actually in a much
shorter tube, well,

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:07.260 align:middle line:84%
then in my original
picture, I could

00:26:07.260 --> 00:26:09.530 align:middle line:84%
cut my set E into
separate pieces

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:13.510 align:middle line:84%
and just look at R-rich tubes
on each of those pieces.

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:17.170 align:middle line:84%
And that could do
some induction.

00:26:17.170 --> 00:26:19.912 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:19.912 --> 00:26:22.180 align:middle line:84%
So then we do a double
counting argument.

00:26:22.180 --> 00:26:28.370 align:middle line:90%


00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:29.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to do--

00:26:29.230 --> 00:26:32.010 align:middle line:90%


00:26:32.010 --> 00:26:37.090 align:middle line:84%
so we're going to count
just pairs of delta balls.

00:26:37.090 --> 00:26:51.410 align:middle line:84%
And so I'll have T of E delta
intersect tubes in T rho.

00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:54.490 align:middle line:84%
So the number of yellow
tubes in this picture.

00:26:54.490 --> 00:26:56.210 align:middle line:90%
Times R squared.

00:26:56.210 --> 00:27:00.450 align:middle line:84%
So I take a tube and I
pick two points in the tube

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:03.890 align:middle line:90%
kind of near opposite ends.

00:27:03.890 --> 00:27:08.040 align:middle line:84%
And for any two points, there is
only one tube that joins them,

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:11.883 align:middle line:84%
so this should be bounded
by R tilde squared.

00:27:11.883 --> 00:27:12.550 align:middle line:90%
Double counting.

00:27:12.550 --> 00:27:20.200 align:middle line:90%


00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:32.040 align:middle line:84%
So we're counting-- we're
counting pairs T, X1, X2, where

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:37.760 align:middle line:84%
T is in this set and
X1 and X2 are in T

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:40.030 align:middle line:90%
and they're near opposite ends.

00:27:40.030 --> 00:27:44.360 align:middle line:90%


00:27:44.360 --> 00:27:45.620 align:middle line:90%
So how many are there?

00:27:45.620 --> 00:27:51.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, for each tube, there are
R squared choices of X1 and X2.

00:27:51.640 --> 00:27:55.360 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
there are only R tilde

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:58.520 align:middle line:90%
squared choices for X1 and X2.

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:02.372 align:middle line:84%
And for each X1 and X2,
there's only one choice of T.

00:28:02.372 --> 00:28:04.220 align:middle line:90%
So this is bounded by this.

00:28:04.220 --> 00:28:07.080 align:middle line:90%


00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:07.920 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:11.440 align:middle line:84%
So double counting
and the Fourier method

00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:13.000 align:middle line:84%
are the two
foundational approaches

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.900 align:middle line:84%
that we did at the
beginning of the class.

00:28:14.900 --> 00:28:16.567 align:middle line:84%
This one was short
enough that I thought

00:28:16.567 --> 00:28:18.940 align:middle line:90%
I could recall it for us.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:23.580 align:middle line:90%


00:28:23.580 --> 00:28:24.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:30.000 align:middle line:90%


00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:30.540 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:46.240 align:middle line:84%
So now TR of E delta is bounded
by maybe sum on R tilde bigger

00:28:46.240 --> 00:28:48.680 align:middle line:90%
than R dyadic.

00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:54.400 align:middle line:84%
We're going to look
at TR tilde of E rho.

00:28:54.400 --> 00:28:57.950 align:middle line:84%
But then we'll multiply
by R tilde over R squared.

00:28:57.950 --> 00:29:01.200 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:01.910 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:29:01.910 --> 00:29:02.910 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:05.790 align:middle line:84%
So every R-rich
delta tube, if you

00:29:05.790 --> 00:29:07.910 align:middle line:84%
thicken it up to
be a rho tube, it

00:29:07.910 --> 00:29:10.730 align:middle line:84%
will be an R
tilde-rich rho tube.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:14.550 align:middle line:84%
And R tilde will be at
least R. So they're all in

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:16.750 align:middle line:90%
here somewhere.

00:29:16.750 --> 00:29:21.150 align:middle line:84%
And in each one of these
guys, there's at most

00:29:21.150 --> 00:29:25.950 align:middle line:90%
this many R-rich delta tubes.

00:29:25.950 --> 00:29:27.550 align:middle line:90%
This is bounded by this.

00:29:27.550 --> 00:29:30.950 align:middle line:84%
And then if we plug in our
bounds, everything will work.

00:29:30.950 --> 00:29:40.270 align:middle line:84%
So this is bounded by N squared
over R times R tilde squared.

00:29:40.270 --> 00:29:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And then we have R tilde
squared over R squared.

00:29:44.910 --> 00:29:47.910 align:middle line:90%
Just cancels.

00:29:47.910 --> 00:29:51.755 align:middle line:84%
And we get N squared
over R cubed.

00:29:51.755 --> 00:29:53.380 align:middle line:84%
And that's the end
of the proof sketch.

00:29:53.380 --> 00:30:05.140 align:middle line:90%


00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:05.660 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:05.660 --> 00:30:06.800 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: What is the sum?

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:09.820 align:middle line:90%


00:30:09.820 --> 00:30:13.100 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: The sum has
logarithmically many terms,

00:30:13.100 --> 00:30:16.060 align:middle line:90%
and so it gets absorbed.

00:30:16.060 --> 00:30:17.200 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I should write that.

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:18.260 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:20.600 align:middle line:84%
That's gets absorbed
in the last step.

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:33.280 align:middle line:90%


00:30:33.280 --> 00:30:33.780 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:40.460 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the only part
where we use that is well space,

00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:45.702 align:middle line:84%
it's like the delta
rho [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:45.702 --> 00:30:49.200 align:middle line:90%
is the only place we're using.

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:50.700 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
so the question

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:53.220 align:middle line:84%
is, where did we
use its well spaced?

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:56.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
instructive to trace where

00:30:56.220 --> 00:30:58.060 align:middle line:90%
we used all the hypotheses.

00:30:58.060 --> 00:31:03.940 align:middle line:90%
So let's label this WS.

00:31:03.940 --> 00:31:05.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's label
it well spaced.

00:31:05.430 --> 00:31:08.340 align:middle line:90%


00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.380 align:middle line:90%
Which we can abbreviate WS.

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:12.340 align:middle line:84%
So where did we use
that as well space?

00:31:12.340 --> 00:31:15.020 align:middle line:90%


00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:18.220 align:middle line:90%
We used it here.

00:31:18.220 --> 00:31:19.350 align:middle line:90%
And that's the only place.

00:31:19.350 --> 00:31:21.860 align:middle line:90%


00:31:21.860 --> 00:31:31.100 align:middle line:84%
So this guy is N. That's
the only place that we used.

00:31:31.100 --> 00:31:32.032 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:32.032 --> 00:31:40.680 align:middle line:84%
We had another hypothesis
that R is bigger than average.

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:45.580 align:middle line:90%


00:31:45.580 --> 00:31:47.620 align:middle line:90%
R bigger than average.

00:31:47.620 --> 00:31:49.620 align:middle line:84%
I have, unfortunately,
hidden a little bit

00:31:49.620 --> 00:31:51.980 align:middle line:90%
where we used that hypothesis.

00:31:51.980 --> 00:31:56.370 align:middle line:84%
But it was in this
Fourier estimate.

00:31:56.370 --> 00:32:02.570 align:middle line:84%
So here we use R big and
perhaps a little bit--

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:04.470 align:middle line:84%
we might use a little
bit of well, space too.

00:32:04.470 --> 00:32:08.930 align:middle line:84%
Although we don't need anything
as strong as what's up there.

00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:10.730 align:middle line:90%
Where did R big come in?

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:13.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, we had all
these tubes and we

00:32:13.330 --> 00:32:16.330 align:middle line:84%
took some of the characteristic
functions of the tubes, smoothed

00:32:16.330 --> 00:32:19.188 align:middle line:84%
out a little bit and we did
Fourier analysis with them.

00:32:19.188 --> 00:32:21.730 align:middle line:84%
And there was a high frequency
part and a low frequency part,

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:24.490 align:middle line:90%
and some middle frequencies.

00:32:24.490 --> 00:32:27.390 align:middle line:84%
This is the contribution
of the high frequency part.

00:32:27.390 --> 00:32:28.870 align:middle line:84%
The high frequency
part dominates,

00:32:28.870 --> 00:32:31.130 align:middle line:90%
immediately you get this.

00:32:31.130 --> 00:32:35.170 align:middle line:84%
The very low frequencies
corresponds--

00:32:35.170 --> 00:32:36.950 align:middle line:84%
with the low
frequency dominated,

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:41.240 align:middle line:84%
it would mean that
R was equal to this.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:42.990 align:middle line:84%
And there are some
in-between frequencies,

00:32:42.990 --> 00:32:44.930 align:middle line:84%
so you have to compute a
little bit to see that they're

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:46.300 align:middle line:90%
controlled by those two cases.

00:32:46.300 --> 00:32:50.890 align:middle line:90%


00:32:50.890 --> 00:32:52.330 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:32:52.330 --> 00:32:53.262 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:32:53.262 --> 00:32:55.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Perhaps because the
Fourier method doesn't really

00:32:55.720 --> 00:32:57.600 align:middle line:84%
need well-spacing
condition, but would it

00:32:57.600 --> 00:33:01.360 align:middle line:84%
be possible to use well-spacing
condition to put a cap

00:33:01.360 --> 00:33:03.900 align:middle line:90%
on the high frequency domain?

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:09.100 align:middle line:84%
Because it seems like
if the frequency is

00:33:09.100 --> 00:33:10.920 align:middle line:84%
corresponding to
the delta balls,

00:33:10.920 --> 00:33:14.050 align:middle line:84%
it should be low if the delta
balls are very small space.

00:33:14.050 --> 00:33:18.187 align:middle line:90%


00:33:18.187 --> 00:33:20.520 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So the question
is about the relationship

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:24.480 align:middle line:84%
between the spacing of E and
the frequencies in the Fourier

00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:26.500 align:middle line:84%
transform of E. Is
that the question?

00:33:26.500 --> 00:33:27.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:33.020 align:middle line:90%


00:33:33.020 --> 00:33:37.040 align:middle line:84%
So if you just took
one delta ball here

00:33:37.040 --> 00:33:39.313 align:middle line:84%
and you smoothed out its
characteristic function,

00:33:39.313 --> 00:33:41.480 align:middle line:84%
it would have a Fourier
transform that was supported

00:33:41.480 --> 00:33:44.200 align:middle line:90%
on a delta inverse bar.

00:33:44.200 --> 00:33:45.920 align:middle line:90%
Now we have a bunch of them.

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:47.800 align:middle line:84%
And so each of them
has a Fourier transform

00:33:47.800 --> 00:33:49.700 align:middle line:84%
that's supported on
a delta inverse ball.

00:33:49.700 --> 00:33:52.270 align:middle line:84%
And now we're going
to add them all up.

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:54.630 align:middle line:84%
Now when we add them all up,
what happens is complicated

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:57.670 align:middle line:84%
and it depends on exactly
where we put them all.

00:33:57.670 --> 00:34:00.190 align:middle line:84%
But absent any
detailed information

00:34:00.190 --> 00:34:02.030 align:middle line:84%
about exactly where
we put them all,

00:34:02.030 --> 00:34:05.190 align:middle line:84%
you would typically expect that
they would have maybe square

00:34:05.190 --> 00:34:07.230 align:middle line:84%
root cancellation and
that the sum would still

00:34:07.230 --> 00:34:10.370 align:middle line:84%
be pretty evenly spread
over a delta inverse point.

00:34:10.370 --> 00:34:16.710 align:middle line:90%


00:34:16.710 --> 00:34:17.210 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:17.210 --> 00:34:18.630 align:middle line:84%
So being well
spaced, we would see

00:34:18.630 --> 00:34:20.203 align:middle line:90%
quite a lot of high frequency.

00:34:20.203 --> 00:34:21.870 align:middle line:84%
But I don't know that
we could recognize

00:34:21.870 --> 00:34:24.750 align:middle line:90%
whether we were well spaced.

00:34:24.750 --> 00:34:27.489 align:middle line:84%
I guess if you had more
points closer together,

00:34:27.489 --> 00:34:29.320 align:middle line:84%
you would see more
low frequency stuff.

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:36.550 align:middle line:90%


00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:37.110 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:34:37.110 --> 00:34:38.279 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:34:38.279 --> 00:34:45.429 align:middle line:90%


00:34:45.429 --> 00:34:45.949 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:49.270 align:middle line:84%
I had, myself, a
couple comments.

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:52.270 align:middle line:84%
So one thing was, it seemed
kind of magical to me

00:34:52.270 --> 00:34:56.670 align:middle line:84%
that we ended up with
the right answer.

00:34:56.670 --> 00:35:02.270 align:middle line:84%
And looking back, in all the
proofs of anything related

00:35:02.270 --> 00:35:05.630 align:middle line:84%
to Szemerédi-Trotter, it seems
rather magical to me that we get

00:35:05.630 --> 00:35:07.550 align:middle line:90%
the right answer.

00:35:07.550 --> 00:35:10.772 align:middle line:84%
So the Szemerédi-Trotter,
or this theorem,

00:35:10.772 --> 00:35:11.730 align:middle line:90%
there's a construction.

00:35:11.730 --> 00:35:12.750 align:middle line:90%
You take a grid.

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:14.530 align:middle line:84%
You take some lines
at rational slopes.

00:35:14.530 --> 00:35:16.613 align:middle line:84%
You compute a little bit
and you see what happens.

00:35:16.613 --> 00:35:18.750 align:middle line:84%
And you get this N
squared over R cubed.

00:35:18.750 --> 00:35:20.350 align:middle line:84%
Then independently
from that, you

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:24.310 align:middle line:84%
look at some cell partitions
or some this or some that,

00:35:24.310 --> 00:35:28.323 align:middle line:84%
or some Fourier analysis and
with completely unrelated

00:35:28.323 --> 00:35:29.490 align:middle line:90%
argument, you get something.

00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:32.410 align:middle line:84%
And if you're lucky, it's
N squared over R cubed.

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:35.730 align:middle line:90%
And we declare victory.

00:35:35.730 --> 00:35:39.910 align:middle line:84%
In all the cases, I don't
really understand why we

00:35:39.910 --> 00:35:43.510 align:middle line:90%
are getting the right answer.

00:35:43.510 --> 00:35:45.470 align:middle line:84%
And it's perhaps
worth mentioning that

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:48.580 align:middle line:84%
Szemerédi-Trotter has
many cousin problems,

00:35:48.580 --> 00:35:50.760 align:middle line:84%
which are almost
as simple to state,

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:53.900 align:middle line:84%
but no one knows
the right answer.

00:35:53.900 --> 00:35:57.900 align:middle line:84%
So for instance, if you replace
straight lines with circles

00:35:57.900 --> 00:36:01.780 align:middle line:84%
or degree 2 curves
or unit circles,

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:05.980 align:middle line:84%
or make up your favorite
class of curves,

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:08.820 align:middle line:84%
you get natural questions
that people have studied hard

00:36:08.820 --> 00:36:13.220 align:middle line:84%
and almost every one of them we
cannot prove matching examples

00:36:13.220 --> 00:36:15.380 align:middle line:90%
and upper bounds.

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:21.580 align:middle line:84%
So it is plausible that
there is no deep reason why

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:26.020 align:middle line:84%
this bound matches the example,
but that we were just lucky.

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:26.660 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:29.200 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Most of other
variations of the problem,

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:32.300 align:middle line:84%
is it harder to
show a similar bound

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:37.403 align:middle line:84%
or to find examples analogous to
the kind of different problem?

00:36:37.403 --> 00:36:38.820 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So
the question is,

00:36:38.820 --> 00:36:40.820 align:middle line:84%
for all these other
variations, is

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:46.530 align:middle line:84%
it harder to prove upper bounds
or harder to find good examples?

00:36:46.530 --> 00:36:50.010 align:middle line:84%
In all these problems,
all of the known examples

00:36:50.010 --> 00:36:52.450 align:middle line:84%
look a lot like
the grid example.

00:36:52.450 --> 00:36:55.025 align:middle line:84%
They involve grids
of points, and you

00:36:55.025 --> 00:36:57.650 align:middle line:84%
try to intersect it with a lot
of circles or a lot of parabolas

00:36:57.650 --> 00:36:59.530 align:middle line:90%
or what have you.

00:36:59.530 --> 00:37:01.913 align:middle line:90%
And there's some upper bound.

00:37:01.913 --> 00:37:03.330 align:middle line:84%
And the proofs of
the upper bounds

00:37:03.330 --> 00:37:06.230 align:middle line:84%
are not so different from the
proofs that we have shown.

00:37:06.230 --> 00:37:09.930 align:middle line:84%
But the numbers that come
up, they just don't match.

00:37:09.930 --> 00:37:13.690 align:middle line:84%
And popular opinion
probably is on the side

00:37:13.690 --> 00:37:15.970 align:middle line:84%
that the upper bound
should be improved.

00:37:15.970 --> 00:37:17.750 align:middle line:84%
But we are talking
about open problems.

00:37:17.750 --> 00:37:18.500 align:middle line:90%
So nobody knows.

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:23.170 align:middle line:90%


00:37:23.170 --> 00:37:23.810 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:23.810 --> 00:37:25.770 align:middle line:90%
So that's one comment.

00:37:25.770 --> 00:37:28.770 align:middle line:84%
Another comment is that in
the context of the Furstenberg

00:37:28.770 --> 00:37:30.650 align:middle line:84%
problem, there is
a key difficulty

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:33.750 align:middle line:84%
that the Furstenberg problem was
false over the complex numbers.

00:37:33.750 --> 00:37:34.930 align:middle line:90%
The Furstenberg conjecture.

00:37:34.930 --> 00:37:36.430 align:middle line:84%
But it's true over
the real numbers.

00:37:36.430 --> 00:37:38.130 align:middle line:84%
So always on the
lookout for what steps

00:37:38.130 --> 00:37:41.090 align:middle line:84%
distinguish the real numbers
from the complex numbers.

00:37:41.090 --> 00:37:43.290 align:middle line:84%
This argument does
not distinguish them.

00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:45.090 align:middle line:84%
This statement can
be-- you can replace

00:37:45.090 --> 00:37:47.130 align:middle line:84%
all the R's with C's
and adjust a few things

00:37:47.130 --> 00:37:48.810 align:middle line:90%
and it's still true.

00:37:48.810 --> 00:37:53.010 align:middle line:84%
So this part of the proof is
not helping with that issue.

00:37:53.010 --> 00:37:53.890 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:37:53.890 --> 00:37:56.250 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:37:56.250 --> 00:37:56.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:56.750 --> 00:38:00.130 align:middle line:90%


00:38:00.130 --> 00:38:03.450 align:middle line:84%
So that was part 1 of the class,
the well-spaced case using

00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:06.370 align:middle line:90%
the Fourier method.

00:38:06.370 --> 00:38:09.930 align:middle line:84%
Part 2 combining all
the stuff we've done.

00:38:09.930 --> 00:38:12.930 align:middle line:84%
Let's start by remembering what
is the big theorem that we're

00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:14.270 align:middle line:90%
discussing the proof of.

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:16.708 align:middle line:84%
And then what are all the
things that we've done.

00:38:16.708 --> 00:38:18.250 align:middle line:84%
In the last part
we'll talk about how

00:38:18.250 --> 00:38:21.110 align:middle line:90%
to put the pieces together.

00:38:21.110 --> 00:38:21.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:21.610 --> 00:38:48.000 align:middle line:90%


00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:49.080 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:52.470 align:middle line:84%
So here is the big theorem
that we would like to prove.

00:38:52.470 --> 00:38:56.080 align:middle line:90%


00:38:56.080 --> 00:39:04.110 align:middle line:84%
So if E is a delta T set
in the unit ball in R2.

00:39:04.110 --> 00:39:06.720 align:middle line:90%


00:39:06.720 --> 00:39:12.280 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that the size
of E is delta to the minus T.

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:25.240 align:middle line:84%
And then for every point in E,
TX is a delta S set of tubes

00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:26.720 align:middle line:90%
through the point x.

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:28.640 align:middle line:84%
And there's no
loss of generality

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:32.720 align:middle line:84%
in assuming that this is
delta E to the minus S.

00:39:32.720 --> 00:39:40.352 align:middle line:84%
Put them all together to
make a set of tubes T. OK.

00:39:40.352 --> 00:39:47.150 align:middle line:84%
And then thinking about how
these tubes intersect E. So

00:39:47.150 --> 00:39:54.670 align:middle line:84%
let's say R is the typical
value of E intersect T delta

00:39:54.670 --> 00:39:58.878 align:middle line:84%
covering number
typical over T and T.

00:39:58.878 --> 00:40:00.170 align:middle line:90%
Could mean average if you like.

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:04.330 align:middle line:84%
But after a little
bit of pigeonholing,

00:40:04.330 --> 00:40:09.190 align:middle line:84%
we can assume that they're all
about the same as each other.

00:40:09.190 --> 00:40:10.540 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:10.540 --> 00:40:16.010 align:middle line:84%
So then the goal is to
say that R is not too big.

00:40:16.010 --> 00:40:19.190 align:middle line:84%
These tubes can't overlap
the points too much.

00:40:19.190 --> 00:40:22.350 align:middle line:84%
R is bounded by the maximum
of three things corresponding

00:40:22.350 --> 00:40:23.730 align:middle line:90%
to three scenarios.

00:40:23.730 --> 00:40:33.470 align:middle line:90%


00:40:33.470 --> 00:40:34.216 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:34.216 --> 00:40:36.520 align:middle line:90%
So A is the stars example.

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:40.070 align:middle line:90%


00:40:40.070 --> 00:40:42.170 align:middle line:84%
These tubes have nothing
to do with each other.

00:40:42.170 --> 00:40:45.330 align:middle line:84%
So the number of dots
on each tube is just 1.

00:40:45.330 --> 00:40:48.770 align:middle line:84%
That's scenario A. B is
the really interesting one,

00:40:48.770 --> 00:40:50.550 align:middle line:90%
it's the integer grid.

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:53.130 align:middle line:84%
And so this-- we've written
things a little differently

00:40:53.130 --> 00:40:58.110 align:middle line:84%
but this corresponds to the
numerology in Szemerédi-Trotter.

00:40:58.110 --> 00:41:05.050 align:middle line:84%
And C is the regime
where random tubes--

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:05.550 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:07.630 align:middle line:84%
If this set E is really
large, random tube

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:10.630 align:middle line:84%
will hit a lot of
points of E. And this

00:41:10.630 --> 00:41:14.830 align:middle line:84%
set T certainly could be
made out of random tubes.

00:41:14.830 --> 00:41:16.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.300 align:middle line:84%
So that is the theorem
we're trying to prove.

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:20.870 align:middle line:90%


00:41:20.870 --> 00:41:24.550 align:middle line:84%
And we have developed
many techniques and tools

00:41:24.550 --> 00:41:25.690 align:middle line:90%
to work on this theorem.

00:41:25.690 --> 00:41:27.730 align:middle line:84%
And we have proven
many cases of it.

00:41:27.730 --> 00:41:29.980 align:middle line:90%
And let's document that.

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:53.460 align:middle line:90%


00:41:53.460 --> 00:41:55.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:55.060 --> 00:42:01.160 align:middle line:84%
So cases we have
discussed the proof.

00:42:01.160 --> 00:42:08.260 align:middle line:90%


00:42:08.260 --> 00:42:09.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:09.460 --> 00:42:13.280 align:middle line:84%
So there are these A,
B, and C scenarios.

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:15.260 align:middle line:84%
And so we should sort
this theorem according

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:18.100 align:middle line:90%
to who's bigger, A or B or C.

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:23.980 align:middle line:84%
So A dominates,
that's if and only

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:28.700 align:middle line:84%
if, S is greater
than or equal to T.

00:42:28.700 --> 00:42:32.020 align:middle line:84%
Let me write it
actually as T is less--

00:42:32.020 --> 00:42:36.070 align:middle line:84%
S is greater than or equal
to T. And in this case,

00:42:36.070 --> 00:42:38.900 align:middle line:84%
it's true by a double
counting argument.

00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:42.690 align:middle line:90%


00:42:42.690 --> 00:42:50.010 align:middle line:84%
And C dominates if
and only if S plus T

00:42:50.010 --> 00:42:51.810 align:middle line:90%
is greater than or equal to 2.

00:42:51.810 --> 00:42:54.780 align:middle line:84%
And that's also true
by the Fourier method.

00:42:54.780 --> 00:43:01.375 align:middle line:90%


00:43:01.375 --> 00:43:07.130 align:middle line:84%
So B dominates otherwise,
and it's actually

00:43:07.130 --> 00:43:09.370 align:middle line:84%
important to write
down this otherwise.

00:43:09.370 --> 00:43:11.290 align:middle line:90%
So S is between--

00:43:11.290 --> 00:43:15.130 align:middle line:84%
T is between S and 2 minus
S. That's what's left.

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:16.830 align:middle line:90%
And this one we don't know yet.

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:21.050 align:middle line:90%


00:43:21.050 --> 00:43:27.610 align:middle line:84%
But we do know a couple of
special cases of this hard case.

00:43:27.610 --> 00:43:35.220 align:middle line:84%
But we do know if
E is AD regular.

00:43:35.220 --> 00:43:37.810 align:middle line:90%


00:43:37.810 --> 00:43:39.370 align:middle line:84%
So that was my
open-ended Shmerkin.

00:43:39.370 --> 00:43:41.250 align:middle line:90%
We talked about it last time.

00:43:41.250 --> 00:43:47.490 align:middle line:84%
And we do know so it
is true E is regular

00:43:47.490 --> 00:43:51.280 align:middle line:84%
and it is true if
E is well spaced.

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:55.490 align:middle line:90%


00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:57.910 align:middle line:90%
We just talked about.

00:43:57.910 --> 00:44:00.930 align:middle line:84%
And that's striking because
AD regular and well spaced

00:44:00.930 --> 00:44:04.350 align:middle line:84%
are the two extremes in the
way that E could be spaced.

00:44:04.350 --> 00:44:06.230 align:middle line:84%
And the other stuff
is in the middle here.

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:14.150 align:middle line:90%


00:44:14.150 --> 00:44:17.050 align:middle line:84%
So actually, people in the
field have run into this problem

00:44:17.050 --> 00:44:18.020 align:middle line:90%
a number of times.

00:44:18.020 --> 00:44:21.210 align:middle line:90%


00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:21.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:21.710 --> 00:44:24.450 align:middle line:84%
So there are several cousin
problems of this Furstenberg set

00:44:24.450 --> 00:44:24.950 align:middle line:90%
problem.

00:44:24.950 --> 00:44:27.690 align:middle line:84%
There's the Kakeya problem,
which is the most famous.

00:44:27.690 --> 00:44:30.920 align:middle line:84%
There's also the Falconer
distance set problem.

00:44:30.920 --> 00:44:32.840 align:middle line:84%
And in both of those
problems, there

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:34.560 align:middle line:84%
was a period where
people knew how

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:37.045 align:middle line:90%
to do these two extreme cases.

00:44:37.045 --> 00:44:38.920 align:middle line:84%
And we thought-- we
hoped maybe we were close

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:40.712 align:middle line:84%
and we tried to do the
stuff in the middle,

00:44:40.712 --> 00:44:44.480 align:middle line:84%
and it was hard and messy,
and we couldn't do it.

00:44:44.480 --> 00:44:46.460 align:middle line:84%
So an open-ended Shmerkin
wrote their paper.

00:44:46.460 --> 00:44:49.280 align:middle line:84%
They said we solved
the AD regular case,

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:51.200 align:middle line:84%
and we know that previously
some people solved

00:44:51.200 --> 00:44:53.160 align:middle line:84%
the well-spaced case,
and what's left is

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:54.840 align:middle line:90%
to do the stuff in the middle.

00:44:54.840 --> 00:44:58.760 align:middle line:84%
But we're not sure whether
that might be very hard.

00:44:58.760 --> 00:45:00.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:01.140 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:45:01.140 --> 00:45:10.400 align:middle line:90%


00:45:10.400 --> 00:45:13.800 align:middle line:84%
And so the last
idea in the proof

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:15.960 align:middle line:84%
is an idea from
Reyn and Wang how

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:22.360 align:middle line:84%
to break up the general
case into pieces that can

00:45:22.360 --> 00:45:25.103 align:middle line:90%
be handled by these methods.

00:45:25.103 --> 00:45:26.520 align:middle line:84%
The first part of
what they did is

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:30.070 align:middle line:84%
they souped up this
well-spaced case a little bit.

00:45:30.070 --> 00:45:33.590 align:middle line:84%
So they proved
that it's true if E

00:45:33.590 --> 00:45:35.830 align:middle line:84%
is something called
semi well-spaced

00:45:35.830 --> 00:45:39.590 align:middle line:90%
that I will define for you.

00:45:39.590 --> 00:45:41.880 align:middle line:90%
Definition soon.

00:45:41.880 --> 00:45:42.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:42.380 --> 00:45:45.310 align:middle line:90%


00:45:45.310 --> 00:45:48.230 align:middle line:84%
It's a mild
generalization of this.

00:45:48.230 --> 00:45:52.090 align:middle line:84%
And the proof is fairly--
a little more complicated

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:54.950 align:middle line:84%
but it's similar ideas
to what I showed you.

00:45:54.950 --> 00:45:57.910 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't distinguish R
from C. It's the same tools

00:45:57.910 --> 00:45:59.730 align:middle line:90%
that I showed you.

00:45:59.730 --> 00:46:00.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:00.230 --> 00:46:02.150 align:middle line:84%
And then the really
important thing

00:46:02.150 --> 00:46:05.550 align:middle line:84%
is how to put all
these things together.

00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:11.190 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to put
all these things together

00:46:11.190 --> 00:46:15.510 align:middle line:84%
by using a multi-scale
argument, which

00:46:15.510 --> 00:46:17.890 align:middle line:84%
is similar to the
submultiplicative Lemma.

00:46:17.890 --> 00:46:23.310 align:middle line:84%
That was one of the key
things in the AD regular case.

00:46:23.310 --> 00:46:26.870 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind you of that
and draw the important picture

00:46:26.870 --> 00:46:27.370 align:middle line:90%
again.

00:46:27.370 --> 00:46:54.260 align:middle line:90%


00:46:54.260 --> 00:46:55.000 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:59.810 align:middle line:90%
So multi-scale argument.

00:46:59.810 --> 00:47:10.260 align:middle line:90%


00:47:10.260 --> 00:47:11.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:11.100 --> 00:47:12.680 align:middle line:90%
So we're going to have delta--

00:47:12.680 --> 00:47:14.180 align:middle line:84%
we're going to have
some scale which

00:47:14.180 --> 00:47:16.580 align:middle line:90%
is in between delta and rho.

00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:19.180 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
visualize E at this scale

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:20.900 align:middle line:90%
but also at that scale.

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:25.670 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a general
E. But it's uniform.

00:47:25.670 --> 00:47:28.620 align:middle line:90%


00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:32.300 align:middle line:84%
And so I think of it as
having some rho balls.

00:47:32.300 --> 00:47:36.700 align:middle line:90%
So these circles are E rho.

00:47:36.700 --> 00:47:39.170 align:middle line:84%
Inside of each rho ball,
we have some delta balls.

00:47:39.170 --> 00:47:44.300 align:middle line:90%


00:47:44.300 --> 00:47:48.125 align:middle line:84%
So those are the delta
balls in E delta.

00:47:48.125 --> 00:47:48.625 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:48.625 --> 00:47:51.295 align:middle line:90%


00:47:51.295 --> 00:47:53.230 align:middle line:90%
And we have some fat tubes.

00:47:53.230 --> 00:47:59.540 align:middle line:90%


00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:00.700 align:middle line:90%
Like that.

00:48:00.700 --> 00:48:05.180 align:middle line:84%
So those are the
tubes that scale rho.

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:07.810 align:middle line:84%
Inside of the fat tubes
we have some thin tubes.

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:10.660 align:middle line:90%


00:48:10.660 --> 00:48:12.534 align:middle line:84%
I should draw it a
little differently.

00:48:12.534 --> 00:48:27.850 align:middle line:90%


00:48:27.850 --> 00:48:30.040 align:middle line:90%
So those are the delta tubes.

00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:33.956 align:middle line:90%


00:48:33.956 --> 00:48:36.410 align:middle line:90%
Now what do we notice?

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:40.170 align:middle line:84%
We notice that the
R that's associated

00:48:40.170 --> 00:48:47.590 align:middle line:84%
to E delta and T delta can
be bounded by a coarse scale.

00:48:47.590 --> 00:48:50.130 align:middle line:84%
So this R is how many
delta balls are there

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:53.090 align:middle line:90%
in an orange tube like this?

00:48:53.090 --> 00:48:56.610 align:middle line:84%
So first, we can ask,
how many rho balls

00:48:56.610 --> 00:48:59.210 align:middle line:90%
does the orange tube have?

00:48:59.210 --> 00:49:05.410 align:middle line:84%
So that would be
R of E rho T rho.

00:49:05.410 --> 00:49:08.010 align:middle line:84%
And then we look inside
each of those rho balls

00:49:08.010 --> 00:49:10.010 align:middle line:90%
at this short delta tube.

00:49:10.010 --> 00:49:13.850 align:middle line:84%
And we ask, how many
delta balls does it hit?

00:49:13.850 --> 00:49:18.490 align:middle line:84%
And let's call one of these
balls B, the typical rho ball.

00:49:18.490 --> 00:49:22.240 align:middle line:90%
And that will be R of EB TB.

00:49:22.240 --> 00:49:25.200 align:middle line:90%


00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:28.400 align:middle line:90%
What is EB TB?

00:49:28.400 --> 00:49:33.280 align:middle line:84%
So EB is just E
intersect B. And then

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:38.680 align:middle line:84%
let's rescale it so that
B becomes a unit ball.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:42.200 align:middle line:90%
And TB is you take T--

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:47.200 align:middle line:84%
well, you take T
intersect B, where

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:50.760 align:middle line:84%
T is in T. You take all
these little pieces of tubes

00:49:50.760 --> 00:49:56.680 align:middle line:84%
and then again you rescale so
that B becomes the unit ball.

00:49:56.680 --> 00:50:03.760 align:middle line:84%
And so EB is a set of
delta over rho balls.

00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:09.440 align:middle line:84%
And TB is a set of
delta over rho tubes.

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:12.340 align:middle line:84%
We do this rescaling
so we can relate this.

00:50:12.340 --> 00:50:14.820 align:middle line:84%
Think of this as a case
of our original problem.

00:50:14.820 --> 00:50:17.000 align:middle line:90%
We can use induction.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:17.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:17.500 --> 00:50:20.760 align:middle line:84%
But this inequality is just
how many delta balls are there

00:50:20.760 --> 00:50:21.840 align:middle line:90%
in the orange tube?

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:24.000 align:middle line:84%
Well, how many rho
balls does it hit

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.240 align:middle line:84%
and how many delta balls
are in each rho ball?

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:30.800 align:middle line:90%


00:50:30.800 --> 00:50:31.920 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:37.560 align:middle line:84%
So by this multi-scale argument,
we can take our original problem

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:39.360 align:middle line:90%
and break it up into pieces.

00:50:39.360 --> 00:50:42.400 align:middle line:84%
We get to choose rho, so we
have some flexibility there.

00:50:42.400 --> 00:50:43.540 align:middle line:90%
Then we can repeat that.

00:50:43.540 --> 00:50:46.160 align:middle line:84%
We can break these up
into pieces and so on.

00:50:46.160 --> 00:50:50.360 align:middle line:84%
And we would be very happy
if all of these pieces

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:54.400 align:middle line:84%
are in the list of things
that we understand.

00:50:54.400 --> 00:50:57.000 align:middle line:84%
And then we could multiply
together all those bounds

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:58.060 align:middle line:90%
and get a bound.

00:50:58.060 --> 00:51:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And in some cases, we'll
get the sharp bound.

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:02.830 align:middle line:84%
And then that's how
they prove the theorem.

00:51:02.830 --> 00:51:05.520 align:middle line:90%


00:51:05.520 --> 00:51:07.152 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:07.152 --> 00:51:10.000 align:middle line:84%
Now to keep track
of what happens,

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:13.360 align:middle line:84%
everything is described in
terms of the branching function.

00:51:13.360 --> 00:51:15.760 align:middle line:84%
And for people's
intuition, it has

00:51:15.760 --> 00:51:17.510 align:middle line:84%
been very helpful
to draw pictures

00:51:17.510 --> 00:51:19.180 align:middle line:84%
of the graph of the
branching function.

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:38.230 align:middle line:90%


00:51:38.230 --> 00:51:39.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:42.980 align:middle line:84%
Do graph of the
branching function.

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:46.910 align:middle line:90%


00:51:46.910 --> 00:51:50.630 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to suppose
that E is uniform.

00:51:50.630 --> 00:51:52.350 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm going
to draw a graph that

00:51:52.350 --> 00:51:55.230 align:middle line:84%
encodes the information of
how many rho balls there

00:51:55.230 --> 00:51:57.910 align:middle line:90%
are to cover E at every scale.

00:51:57.910 --> 00:52:00.470 align:middle line:84%
So on this axis,
I want to put rho.

00:52:00.470 --> 00:52:05.830 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm going to
put is log delta of rho.

00:52:05.830 --> 00:52:10.270 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to be a
number between 0 and 1.

00:52:10.270 --> 00:52:15.620 align:middle line:84%
And now on this axis, I want to
understand the covering number E

00:52:15.620 --> 00:52:16.380 align:middle line:90%
rho.

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:19.700 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm going to put here
is the logarithm in the base 1

00:52:19.700 --> 00:52:24.060 align:middle line:84%
over delta of this
covering number.

00:52:24.060 --> 00:52:26.712 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:26.712 --> 00:52:36.660 align:middle line:84%
So if E delta or
delta to the minus T,

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:38.500 align:middle line:84%
then when you plug
in 1 here, that

00:52:38.500 --> 00:52:40.240 align:middle line:90%
corresponds to the scale delta.

00:52:40.240 --> 00:52:42.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is delta
E to the minus T.

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:46.140 align:middle line:84%
So this logarithm
would be T of this.

00:52:46.140 --> 00:52:48.660 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to call
this variable T--

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:50.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to call
this variable X.

00:52:50.500 --> 00:52:55.180 align:middle line:84%
And this is F of X. F is
the branching function.

00:52:55.180 --> 00:52:56.580 align:middle line:90%
So if E of--

00:52:56.580 --> 00:52:59.740 align:middle line:84%
E delta is delta E to the
minus T, it means F of 1

00:52:59.740 --> 00:53:13.580 align:middle line:84%
equals T. If E is a delta T
set, then it means that F of X

00:53:13.580 --> 00:53:17.660 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than T
times X. So here's

00:53:17.660 --> 00:53:26.460 align:middle line:84%
the straight line with slope
T. And I'll put this in blue.

00:53:26.460 --> 00:53:30.580 align:middle line:84%
F of X is bigger than T times
X. There are many things

00:53:30.580 --> 00:53:33.520 align:middle line:84%
that we could draw that
do that, maybe like that.

00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:43.282 align:middle line:90%


00:53:43.282 --> 00:53:46.300 align:middle line:84%
So these pictures
always start at 1.

00:53:46.300 --> 00:53:49.940 align:middle line:84%
Because when X is 1, it means
we're talking about the scale

00:53:49.940 --> 00:53:51.540 align:middle line:90%
rho equals 1.

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:54.200 align:middle line:84%
And this is a subset
of the unit ball.

00:53:54.200 --> 00:53:58.100 align:middle line:84%
So that's the covering
number at scale 1 is 1.

00:53:58.100 --> 00:53:59.320 align:middle line:90%
So it always starts there.

00:53:59.320 --> 00:54:04.100 align:middle line:90%


00:54:04.100 --> 00:54:07.380 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or
comments about these,

00:54:07.380 --> 00:54:08.530 align:middle line:90%
setting this up as a graph?

00:54:08.530 --> 00:54:11.450 align:middle line:90%


00:54:11.450 --> 00:54:12.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:12.650 --> 00:54:17.330 align:middle line:84%
So now what do we know
about this function F?

00:54:17.330 --> 00:54:21.230 align:middle line:84%
So F is monotonically
increasing.

00:54:21.230 --> 00:54:24.490 align:middle line:90%


00:54:24.490 --> 00:54:25.490 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:54:25.490 --> 00:54:27.590 align:middle line:84%
As we go this way,
rho is getting smaller

00:54:27.590 --> 00:54:31.690 align:middle line:84%
and the rho covering number
is only going to get bigger.

00:54:31.690 --> 00:54:35.850 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't
increase too quickly.

00:54:35.850 --> 00:54:41.730 align:middle line:84%
So F of X plus
delta X is less than

00:54:41.730 --> 00:54:46.190 align:middle line:84%
or equal to F of X plus 2
delta X. So F is 2 Lipschitz.

00:54:46.190 --> 00:54:48.770 align:middle line:90%


00:54:48.770 --> 00:54:49.450 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:54:49.450 --> 00:54:54.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, if we have a rho ball
and then we decrease rho,

00:54:54.650 --> 00:54:58.810 align:middle line:84%
we can always cover that with
a certain number of rho tilde

00:54:58.810 --> 00:55:00.850 align:middle line:90%
balls.

00:55:00.850 --> 00:55:07.170 align:middle line:84%
So B rho is covered by
rho tilde rho over--

00:55:07.170 --> 00:55:10.520 align:middle line:84%
so if rho tilde
is less than rho,

00:55:10.520 --> 00:55:16.080 align:middle line:84%
then B rho is covered by rho
over rho tilde squared rho tilde

00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:18.480 align:middle line:90%
balls.

00:55:18.480 --> 00:55:20.580 align:middle line:84%
And we may or may
not need all of them,

00:55:20.580 --> 00:55:22.420 align:middle line:84%
but the most we could
need is all of them.

00:55:22.420 --> 00:55:26.560 align:middle line:84%
And that would correspond
to equality here.

00:55:26.560 --> 00:55:28.100 align:middle line:90%
So F is 2 Lipschitz.

00:55:28.100 --> 00:55:30.540 align:middle line:90%


00:55:30.540 --> 00:55:31.040 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:33.087 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the 2 comes
from the dimension?

00:55:33.087 --> 00:55:34.920 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Two comes
from the dimension.

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:38.240 align:middle line:84%
This 2 is this 2, which
comes from the dimension.

00:55:38.240 --> 00:55:38.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, OK.

00:55:38.740 --> 00:55:39.282 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:55:39.282 --> 00:55:43.680 align:middle line:84%
So let me say E is uniform, E
is contained in the unit ball,

00:55:43.680 --> 00:55:46.060 align:middle line:90%
and E is in two dimensions.

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:48.310 align:middle line:84%
And if you change this
2 to a D dimension,

00:55:48.310 --> 00:55:50.560 align:middle line:84%
the only thing in this
discussion that would change is

00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:53.000 align:middle line:90%
that these 2's would become D's.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:53.900 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thank you.

00:55:53.900 --> 00:55:57.840 align:middle line:90%


00:55:57.840 --> 00:55:59.780 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, good.

00:55:59.780 --> 00:56:00.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:00.280 --> 00:56:04.400 align:middle line:84%
So to get a feel
for this, I will

00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:10.870 align:middle line:84%
draw a few pictures of the
branching functions for cases

00:56:10.870 --> 00:56:14.150 align:middle line:90%
