00:59:29.610 --> 00:59:32.530 align:middle line:84%
What is the relationship
between this branching function

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:34.930 align:middle line:90%
and these branching functions?

00:59:34.930 --> 00:59:37.380 align:middle line:84%
The relationship
is really simple.

00:59:37.380 --> 00:59:54.730 align:middle line:90%


00:59:54.730 --> 01:00:01.290 align:middle line:84%
So F of X itself, this is the
branching function of E delta.

01:00:01.290 --> 01:00:04.610 align:middle line:90%
And it looks like something.

01:00:04.610 --> 01:00:05.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:05.110 --> 01:00:07.170 align:middle line:90%
It could be anything.

01:00:07.170 --> 01:00:09.110 align:middle line:90%
And then we have this scale rho.

01:00:09.110 --> 01:00:13.770 align:middle line:84%
So over here is
log delta of rho.

01:00:13.770 --> 01:00:17.530 align:middle line:84%
And if you think
about this set E rho,

01:00:17.530 --> 01:00:22.188 align:middle line:84%
well, it's just the
branching function of E rho

01:00:22.188 --> 01:00:24.230 align:middle line:84%
is the same as the branching
function of E delta.

01:00:24.230 --> 01:00:25.510 align:middle line:90%
Except it just stops at rho.

01:00:25.510 --> 01:00:28.170 align:middle line:84%
And we don't look at
any smaller scales.

01:00:28.170 --> 01:00:37.370 align:middle line:84%
So this here in orange is
basically the branching function

01:00:37.370 --> 01:00:38.190 align:middle line:90%
of E rho.

01:00:38.190 --> 01:00:45.090 align:middle line:90%


01:00:45.090 --> 01:00:50.433 align:middle line:84%
Then we look inside of this
ball and we look at all of the--

01:00:50.433 --> 01:00:51.850 align:middle line:84%
start at the scale
rho and then we

01:00:51.850 --> 01:00:54.530 align:middle line:84%
look at all of the
smaller scales of E.

01:00:54.530 --> 01:01:01.560 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here is--

01:01:01.560 --> 01:01:06.520 align:middle line:90%
let me say this describes F EB.

01:01:06.520 --> 01:01:08.590 align:middle line:84%
This is basically the
branching function of EB.

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:16.080 align:middle line:90%


01:01:16.080 --> 01:01:17.220 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

01:01:17.220 --> 01:01:19.832 align:middle line:90%


01:01:19.832 --> 01:01:22.360 align:middle line:90%
So what's the situation?

01:01:22.360 --> 01:01:25.960 align:middle line:84%
We begin with an arbitrary
branching function

01:01:25.960 --> 01:01:28.720 align:middle line:90%
that just obeys this condition.

01:01:28.720 --> 01:01:30.040 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:01:30.040 --> 01:01:33.920 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Going back
to the multi-scale

01:01:33.920 --> 01:01:39.300 align:middle line:84%
or the submultiplicative Lemma,
why is it-- like the second one,

01:01:39.300 --> 01:01:42.990 align:middle line:84%
the R of EB TB when it's like
the number of delta balls

01:01:42.990 --> 01:01:45.400 align:middle line:90%
is the same in the rho ball.

01:01:45.400 --> 01:01:48.245 align:middle line:90%
They have the same.

01:01:48.245 --> 01:01:49.120 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

01:01:49.120 --> 01:01:49.892 align:middle line:90%
Right.

01:01:49.892 --> 01:01:55.670 align:middle line:84%
So this R of EB TB
is supposed to be

01:01:55.670 --> 01:02:01.230 align:middle line:84%
