01:03:03.100 --> 01:03:05.580 align:middle line:90%
in each of those bits.

01:03:05.580 --> 01:03:08.980 align:middle line:84%
So now we have some tubes
at this tubes inside of B

01:03:08.980 --> 01:03:12.060 align:middle line:84%
and points inside of
B. And we blow that up.

01:03:12.060 --> 01:03:13.000 align:middle line:90%
And that's over here.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:15.980 align:middle line:90%


01:03:15.980 --> 01:03:18.700 align:middle line:90%
OK, good

01:03:18.700 --> 01:03:19.200 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:19.200 --> 01:03:21.060 align:middle line:84%
So here's something
we might try.

01:03:21.060 --> 01:03:22.800 align:middle line:90%
We start with E delta T delta.

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:24.200 align:middle line:90%
We don't know how to handle it.

01:03:24.200 --> 01:03:25.860 align:middle line:84%
We look at the
branching function.

01:03:25.860 --> 01:03:27.700 align:middle line:84%
I can cut the branching
function anywhere

01:03:27.700 --> 01:03:30.280 align:middle line:84%
I like and produce two
branching functions.

01:03:30.280 --> 01:03:31.820 align:middle line:90%
And I can repeat that.

01:03:31.820 --> 01:03:34.780 align:middle line:84%
And then I can take the
different branching functions

01:03:34.780 --> 01:03:35.480 align:middle line:90%
I get.

01:03:35.480 --> 01:03:38.540 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, I can
put them into the list

01:03:38.540 --> 01:03:41.260 align:middle line:90%
that I know how to handle.

01:03:41.260 --> 01:03:43.810 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll multiply together
and I'll get an answer.

01:03:43.810 --> 01:03:47.940 align:middle line:90%


01:03:47.940 --> 01:03:51.780 align:middle line:84%
So let me do a couple examples
of this concatenation method

01:03:51.780 --> 01:03:53.070 align:middle line:90%
and we'll see how it works.

01:03:53.070 --> 01:04:12.340 align:middle line:90%


01:04:12.340 --> 01:04:13.950 align:middle line:90%
Concatenation method.

01:04:13.950 --> 01:04:18.780 align:middle line:90%


01:04:18.780 --> 01:04:19.480 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:04:19.480 --> 01:04:23.620 align:middle line:84%
So let me do the example where
our graph consists of two lines.

01:04:23.620 --> 01:04:28.660 align:middle line:84%
So it has a line of
slope T1 up to somewhere.

01:04:28.660 --> 01:04:31.540 align:middle line:90%
So here's log delta of rho.

01:04:31.540 --> 01:04:33.600 align:middle line:84%
And then it has a line
at a different slope,

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:35.460 align:middle line:90%
which let's say is smaller.

01:04:35.460 --> 01:04:41.260 align:middle line:90%
So here's slope T2 to the end.

01:04:41.260 --> 01:04:42.060 align:middle line:90%
It's 1.

01:04:42.060 --> 01:04:48.280 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that
this final height is T.

01:04:48.280 --> 01:04:49.990 align:middle line:90%
So how are they related?

01:04:49.990 --> 01:04:53.410 align:middle line:84%
So delta to the
minus T is E delta,

01:04:53.410 --> 01:04:56.490 align:middle line:84%
which I can read off from
my final branching function.

01:04:56.490 --> 01:05:00.330 align:middle line:84%
That's the size of E rho
times the size of EB.

01:05:00.330 --> 01:05:05.210 align:middle line:84%
Number of rho balls times number
of delta balls per rho ball.

01:05:05.210 --> 01:05:09.330 align:middle line:90%
So that is rho to the minus T1.

01:05:09.330 --> 01:05:11.130 align:middle line:90%
So this is slope T1.

01:05:11.130 --> 01:05:14.460 align:middle line:84%
Times delta over
rho to the minus T2.

01:05:14.460 --> 01:05:19.090 align:middle line:90%


01:05:19.090 --> 01:05:23.290 align:middle line:90%
So now let's see what happens.

01:05:23.290 --> 01:05:35.890 align:middle line:84%
So R of ET is bounded by R
of E rho T rho R of EB TB.

01:05:35.890 --> 01:05:37.150 align:middle line:90%
Scenario 1.

01:05:37.150 --> 01:05:40.330 align:middle line:90%


01:05:40.330 --> 01:05:46.930 align:middle line:84%
In this scenario 1, T1 and T2
are both in this middle range

01:05:46.930 --> 01:05:48.340 align:middle line:90%
where B dominates.

01:05:48.340 --> 01:05:51.160 align:middle line:90%


01:05:51.160 --> 01:05:59.240 align:middle line:84%
So then this guy will
give me rho to the S

01:05:59.240 --> 01:06:03.120 align:middle line:84%
over 2, rho to the
minus T1 over 2.

01:06:03.120 --> 01:06:07.080 align:middle line:84%
Because this is
option B. B dominates.

01:06:07.080 --> 01:06:12.200 align:middle line:84%
And this guy here will give me
delta over rho to the S over 2,

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:16.240 align:middle line:84%
delta over Rho to
the minus T2 over 2.

01:06:16.240 --> 01:06:20.340 align:middle line:84%
Because that's option B.
This is not B as in ball,

01:06:20.340 --> 01:06:24.960 align:middle line:84%
this is B as in A, B,
and C, the three options.

01:06:24.960 --> 01:06:25.740 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:06:25.740 --> 01:06:28.640 align:middle line:84%
When you multiply it out,
something nice happens.

01:06:28.640 --> 01:06:31.640 align:middle line:84%
What happens when we
multiply these together?

01:06:31.640 --> 01:06:35.080 align:middle line:90%
We get delta to the S over 2.

01:06:35.080 --> 01:06:38.160 align:middle line:84%
And what happens when we
