middle, this is the goal.

01:08:17.620 --> 01:08:20.310 align:middle line:90%


01:08:20.310 --> 01:08:22.130 align:middle line:84%
How does this
compare to the goal?

01:08:22.130 --> 01:08:24.510 align:middle line:84%
Not so obvious,
but it's actually

01:08:24.510 --> 01:08:25.770 align:middle line:90%
much bigger than the goal.

01:08:25.770 --> 01:08:27.270 align:middle line:90%
What went wrong?

01:08:27.270 --> 01:08:30.510 align:middle line:84%
Remember that at each
step when I bounded R,

01:08:30.510 --> 01:08:35.710 align:middle line:84%
my theorem bounds R by a
maximum of three things.

01:08:35.710 --> 01:08:42.220 align:middle line:84%
Maximum of A, B,
and C. So this C

01:08:42.220 --> 01:08:45.740 align:middle line:84%
is way bigger than
B in this regime.

01:08:45.740 --> 01:08:49.700 align:middle line:84%
And this A is way bigger
than B in this regime.

01:08:49.700 --> 01:08:52.460 align:middle line:90%
And B times B would be my goal.

01:08:52.460 --> 01:08:53.680 align:middle line:90%
So this is way too big.

01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:56.460 align:middle line:90%
So it doesn't work.

01:08:56.460 --> 01:08:57.218 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:57.218 --> 01:09:01.100 align:middle line:84%
So lesson that we
learned here is

01:09:01.100 --> 01:09:12.720 align:middle line:84%
that we want to break up
F into pieces so that--

01:09:12.720 --> 01:09:13.800 align:middle line:90%
OK, I'll say it in words.

01:09:13.800 --> 01:09:17.220 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, we'd like to
be able to analyze each piece.

01:09:17.220 --> 01:09:19.540 align:middle line:84%
So we want each piece to
be on the list of things

01:09:19.540 --> 01:09:20.317 align:middle line:90%
we understand.

01:09:20.317 --> 01:09:22.359 align:middle line:84%
So if you don't have a
sharp bound for the piece,

01:09:22.359 --> 01:09:24.401 align:middle line:84%
there's no way you're
going to have a sharp bound

01:09:24.401 --> 01:09:25.340 align:middle line:90%
for the whole thing.

01:09:25.340 --> 01:09:28.399 align:middle line:84%
But also, we're not happy
with just any of these.

01:09:28.399 --> 01:09:37.269 align:middle line:84%
We really want them all
to be in case B. Right.

01:09:37.269 --> 01:09:43.460 align:middle line:90%


01:09:43.460 --> 01:09:53.580 align:middle line:84%
So we really want
each piece to be

01:09:53.580 --> 01:10:02.300 align:middle line:84%
either AD regular with T of
that piece in our middle range,

01:10:02.300 --> 01:10:05.190 align:middle line:84%
in the B range, or
semi well spaced.

01:10:05.190 --> 01:10:19.160 align:middle line:90%


01:10:19.160 --> 01:10:19.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:19.660 --> 01:10:24.620 align:middle line:90%


01:10:24.620 --> 01:10:25.120 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:10:25.120 --> 01:10:32.740 align:middle line:90%


01:10:32.740 --> 01:10:36.260 align:middle line:84%
So the very last idea is
that indeed, you can do this.

01:10:36.260 --> 01:10:41.330 align:middle line:84%
You can start with an
arbitrary branching function,

01:10:41.330 --> 01:10:43.650 align:middle line:84%
and then you can break
it up into pieces

01:10:43.650 --> 01:10:47.970 align:middle line:90%
where each piece is like this.

01:10:47.970 --> 01:10:49.310 align:middle line:90%
I'll write it down in a second.

01:10:49.310 --> 01:10:49.977 align:middle line:90%
Draw an example.

01:10:49.977 --> 01:10:53.170 align:middle line:90%


01:10:53.170 --> 01:10:55.610 align:middle line:84%
Probably the most
important idea behind this

01:10:55.610 --> 01:10:57.770 align:middle line:90%
is the Rademacher theorem.

01:10:57.770 --> 01:11:01.430 align:middle line:84%
So the Rademacher theorem says
that a differentiable function--

01:11:01.430 --> 01:11:03.450 align:middle line:84%
a Lipschitz function
is differentiable

01:11:03.450 --> 01:11:05.930 align:middle line:90%
almost everywhere.

01:11:05.930 --> 01:11:09.110 align:middle line:84%
And so this function F, we
don't know a lot about it,

01:11:09.110 --> 01:11:12.170 align:middle line:84%
but we did see that
its Lipschitz function.

01:11:12.170 --> 01:11:14.930 align:middle line:84%
And so it's differentiable
almost everywhere.

01:11:14.930 --> 01:11:17.570 align:middle line:84%
So that means that we
can cut up our interval

01:11:17.570 --> 01:11:20.690 align:middle line:84%
into little intervals
where maybe you

01:11:20.690 --> 01:11:21.950 align:middle line:90%
have to throw out a tiny bit.

01:11:21.950 --> 01:11:23.530 align:middle line:84%
But on almost every
little interval,

01:11:23.530 --> 01:11:28.690 align:middle line:84%
it's approximately a
constant slope example.

01:11:28.690 --> 01:11:32.410 align:middle line:84%
So you can reduce everything--
just by Rademacher theorem,

01:11:32.410 --> 01:11:36.200 align:middle line:84%
you can reduce everything to
the AD regular irregular case.

01:11:36.200 --> 01:11:38.080 align:middle line:84%
And that's an indication
that AD regular case

01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:38.940 align:middle line:90%
is really important.

01:11:38.940 --> 01:11:41.560 align:middle line:90%
It's not just a special case.

01:11:41.560 --> 01:11:44.760 align:middle line:84%
However, if you do
that, we would not only

01:11:44.760 --> 01:11:46.640 align:middle line:84%
have slopes in
here, we would also

01:11:46.640 --> 01:11:49.120 align:middle line:84%
have slopes that are
too small or too large.

01:11:49.120 --> 01:11:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So we want everybody
to be in case B.

01:11:51.480 --> 01:11:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we
need some extra stuff

01:11:53.160 --> 01:11:56.000 align:middle line:90%
like the semi well-spaced.

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:56.772 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:56.772 --> 01:12:01.470 align:middle line:84%
So I will write down
this last thing.

01:12:01.470 --> 01:12:10.080 align:middle line:90%


01:12:10.080 --> 01:12:11.270 align:middle line:90%
So final Lemma.

01:12:11.270 --> 01:12:14.600 align:middle line:90%


01:12:14.600 --> 01:12:19.400 align:middle line:84%
If F is a function
from 0, 1 to R,

01:12:19.400 --> 01:12:23.720 align:middle line:84%
which is 2 Lipschitz
and increasing,

01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:28.840 align:middle line:84%
then we can break up 0,
1 as a disjoint union

01:12:28.840 --> 01:12:33.370 align:middle line:84%
of some intervals, maybe
plus tiny leftover.

01:12:33.370 --> 01:12:37.160 align:middle line:90%


01:12:37.160 --> 01:12:45.760 align:middle line:84%
And then on each I,
either F restricted to I--

01:12:45.760 --> 01:12:55.240 align:middle line:84%
either F is almost
linear with slope TI,

01:12:55.240 --> 01:12:56.930 align:middle line:90%
and TI is in our range.

01:12:56.930 --> 01:13:00.500 align:middle line:90%


01:13:00.500 --> 01:13:02.080 align:middle line:90%
I should say one other thing.

01:13:02.080 --> 01:13:07.480 align:middle line:84%
Let's say F of 1 is T
and T is in our range.

01:13:07.480 --> 01:13:08.023 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

01:13:08.023 --> 01:13:08.940 align:middle line:90%
And we should-- sorry.

01:13:08.940 --> 01:13:12.040 align:middle line:84%
We should have F of X
is bigger than T of X.

01:13:12.040 --> 01:13:13.020 align:middle line:90%
So this is our setup.

01:13:13.020 --> 01:13:14.420 align:middle line:90%
We have a delta T set.

01:13:14.420 --> 01:13:16.920 align:middle line:84%
We're looking at its
branching function.

01:13:16.920 --> 01:13:18.920 align:middle line:84%
So either its almost
linear and its slope

01:13:18.920 --> 01:13:23.330 align:middle line:84%
is in the desired range or
on I, F is semi well spaced.

01:13:23.330 --> 01:13:29.760 align:middle line:90%


01:13:29.760 --> 01:13:31.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:31.950 --> 01:13:34.270 align:middle line:84%
It's not so difficult
to prove once you think

01:13:34.270 --> 01:13:37.310 align:middle line:84%
to try to prove it, but I'm
just going to illustrate it

01:13:37.310 --> 01:13:39.260 align:middle line:90%
with an example.

01:13:39.260 --> 01:13:44.310 align:middle line:90%


01:13:44.310 --> 01:13:48.870 align:middle line:90%
So suppose F looks like this.

01:13:48.870 --> 01:13:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And so the slope is
increasing for a while.

01:13:52.010 --> 01:13:54.790 align:middle line:84%
I guess it needs to start
bigger than T. So a bit tricky

01:13:54.790 --> 01:13:57.830 align:middle line:90%
to draw this picture here.

01:13:57.830 --> 01:14:02.010 align:middle line:84%
So it needs to stay above
this dotted line, right?

01:14:02.010 --> 01:14:04.810 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to start tangent
to the line, which is OK.

01:14:04.810 --> 01:14:07.030 align:middle line:90%
The slope increases for a while.

01:14:07.030 --> 01:14:09.690 align:middle line:84%
Has a maximum slope,
and the slope decreases.

01:14:09.690 --> 01:14:11.150 align:middle line:90%
And it goes like that.

01:14:11.150 --> 01:14:13.510 align:middle line:84%
And as this slope
increases, there

01:14:13.510 --> 01:14:20.542 align:middle line:84%
is a key moment where
the slope gets too big.

01:14:20.542 --> 01:14:26.870 align:middle line:84%
Over here, slope is 2 minus
S. And maybe at the end

01:14:26.870 --> 01:14:29.350 align:middle line:90%
the slope is too small.

01:14:29.350 --> 01:14:34.100 align:middle line:84%
The slope is less than S.
OK, so what should we do?

01:14:34.100 --> 01:14:40.900 align:middle line:84%
Well, this whole thing
here, this whole thing

01:14:40.900 --> 01:14:42.320 align:middle line:90%
is semi well-spaced.

01:14:42.320 --> 01:14:47.420 align:middle line:90%


01:14:47.420 --> 01:14:52.340 align:middle line:84%
And at the beginning we can
take very short intervals.

01:14:52.340 --> 01:14:56.820 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have this guy and
this guy, and this guy.

01:14:56.820 --> 01:15:00.580 align:middle line:90%
And these blue guys are almost--

01:15:00.580 --> 01:15:02.250 align:middle line:84%
they're short, so
it's almost linear.

01:15:02.250 --> 01:15:04.980 align:middle line:90%


01:15:04.980 --> 01:15:08.580 align:middle line:84%
And the slope is not yet
bigger than 2 minus S.

01:15:08.580 --> 01:15:17.980 align:middle line:84%
So the slope TI is less than
2 minus S. Bigger than S. OK.

01:15:17.980 --> 01:15:18.960 align:middle line:90%
This is not a proof.

01:15:18.960 --> 01:15:21.980 align:middle line:84%
But there are not that many
ways this function could look.

01:15:21.980 --> 01:15:25.277 align:middle line:84%
And if you draw five of them,
you can convince yourself.

01:15:25.277 --> 01:15:26.610 align:middle line:90%
Then if you want, you can prove.

01:15:26.610 --> 01:15:30.170 align:middle line:90%


01:15:30.170 --> 01:15:32.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:32.130 --> 01:15:38.890 align:middle line:84%
So to summarize, This
picture, this fact

01:15:38.890 --> 01:15:42.050 align:middle line:84%
is very powerful because it lets
us break up our original problem

01:15:42.050 --> 01:15:44.410 align:middle line:90%
into smaller problems.

01:15:44.410 --> 01:15:47.010 align:middle line:84%
And the smaller problems in
terms of the branching functions

01:15:47.010 --> 01:15:48.570 align:middle line:84%
because the smaller
problems are just

01:15:48.570 --> 01:15:52.090 align:middle line:84%
little pieces of the branching
function of the bigger problem.

01:15:52.090 --> 01:15:53.550 align:middle line:84%
And when you do
that, there are--

01:15:53.550 --> 01:15:57.850 align:middle line:90%


01:15:57.850 --> 01:16:02.530 align:middle line:84%
what originally looked like we
just had a few special cases,

01:16:02.530 --> 01:16:06.610 align:middle line:84%
now we can take any combination
of those few special cases.

01:16:06.610 --> 01:16:08.390 align:middle line:90%
And that turns out to be a lot.

01:16:08.390 --> 01:16:09.710 align:middle line:90%
And even to be everything.

01:16:09.710 --> 01:16:12.410 align:middle line:90%


01:16:12.410 --> 01:16:16.410 align:middle line:90%
So that's the last idea.

01:16:16.410 --> 01:16:16.910 align:middle line:90%
The proof.

01:16:16.910 --> 01:16:18.890 align:middle line:84%
The proof how to put
the pieces together.

01:16:18.890 --> 01:16:21.950 align:middle line:84%
And so these pieces were
not just special cases.

01:16:21.950 --> 01:16:25.250 align:middle line:84%
They are really the
fundamental building blocks

01:16:25.250 --> 01:16:28.210 align:middle line:90%
of the whole story.

01:16:28.210 --> 01:16:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And it also is striking to me
that this multi-scale argument

01:16:32.450 --> 01:16:36.370 align:middle line:84%
was really crucial in both the
AD regular case and the not

01:16:36.370 --> 01:16:38.930 align:middle line:90%
the AD regular case.

01:16:38.930 --> 01:16:42.330 align:middle line:84%
In the AD regular case, these
problems were all the same.

01:16:42.330 --> 01:16:45.230 align:middle line:84%
And then seeing that sameness at
all these different situations,

01:16:45.230 --> 01:16:48.650 align:middle line:84%
it gave us some extra
rigidity and structure.

01:16:48.650 --> 01:16:51.410 align:middle line:84%
In the not AD regular case,
by definition, these problems

01:16:51.410 --> 01:16:52.430 align:middle line:90%
are different.

01:16:52.430 --> 01:16:55.130 align:middle line:84%
And that means that gives
us a whole menu of problems

01:16:55.130 --> 01:16:56.067 align:middle line:90%
to choose from.

01:16:56.067 --> 01:16:57.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we can look
through this menu

01:16:57.650 --> 01:16:59.790 align:middle line:84%
and try to find the
things that we understand.

01:16:59.790 --> 01:17:02.810 align:middle line:90%


01:17:02.810 --> 01:17:04.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:17:04.790 --> 01:17:05.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:05.290 --> 01:17:09.730 align:middle line:84%
So that was an outline
of projection theory.

01:17:09.730 --> 01:17:12.070 align:middle line:84%
Thank you for coming
with me on this outline.

01:17:12.070 --> 01:17:14.410 align:middle line:84%
It's been nice
talking with you all.

01:17:14.410 --> 01:17:17.760 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, let's stop
the class there.

01:17:17.760 --> 01:17:25.000 align:middle line:90%